          "history": [
            {
              "date": "2026-04-13",
              "score": 0.65,
              "questions": 4,
              "correct": 2.6,
              "notes": "FAIL. Q1 (0.6): right intuition (coefficients linear, basis functions not) but imprecise wording \u2014 didn't cleanly state 'linear in the parameters \u03b2' or connect to OLS via design matrix. Q2 (0.5): named boundary/extrapolation blowup but missed OVERFITTING as the primary problem with degree-15 on 50 points; also didn't articulate why tails blow up (x^d dominates for large |x|, sparse leverage at edges). Q3 (0.5): correctly ID'd that x, x^2, x^3 move together so single-variable interpretation is ill-posed, but couldn't propose the alternative (partial derivative df/dx as a function of x, or f(x+1)-f(x) at a specific point). Q4 (1.0): after clarifying what 'nonlinear optimization' means, correctly said FALSE and cited closed-form solution. Re-quiz tomorrow \u2014 drill linearity-in-parameters framing, overfitting vs boundary as distinct concepts, and partial-derivative interpretation."
            },
            {
              "date": "2026-04-17",
              "score": 0.5,
              "questions": 4,
              "correct": 2,
              "notes": "Q1: got param count but not full design matrix dims (n x d+1). Q2: said CI widens but missed point estimate explosion; confused extrapolation with outlier. Q3: overcomplicated linear-in-parameters \u2014 invented separation into linear/nonlinear components. Q4a correct. Q4b vague on why poly wins for smooth curves. Strong conceptual intuition, weak on precise mechanics/definitions."
