              "notes": "FAIL on first real review (diagnostic was shallow - just recognition). Q1 (0.5): delivered the 'outsource proof of identity' slogan despite explicit instruction to avoid it, gave MSU/Okta example but stopped at 'grants access' - missed the IdP's three mechanics (user directory, credential verification, SIGNED ASSERTION). Doesn't yet articulate the cryptographic trust layer (SP verifies IdP's signature on SAML assertion / OIDC id_token via IdP's public cert) - this is what makes SSO work vs. being just a redirect. Q2 (0.45) INTERLEAVED with authn_vs_authz: called nuszco 'an authZ layer' - the classic conflation taught against in 04-15 authn_vs_authz session where the 'SCIM as substrate, not authZ' framing was explicitly delivered. Mark's reflex when a new product fits the substrate role is to label it authZ. The correct 3-party split (IdP=authN, SP=authZ enforcement, nuszco=membership substrate) was re-taught. Also missed bi-directional sync despite it being in the investor_onepager.md Mark had open in the IDE. Q3 (0.2): 'not aware of GitHub's IdP capabilities' - honest non-confabulation but a real gap. GitHub is both SP (company GH org) AND IdP ('Sign in with GitHub' OAuth for Vercel/CircleCI/npm), and a GdP in nuszco's vocabulary. Q4 (stretch, not scored): only recognized Okta from Workday/Entra/Okta - Workday as HRIS system-of-record and Entra as Microsoft's identity directory were new. Re-teach delivered covering IdP mechanics, 3-party split, GitHub multi-role, multi-IdP topology. Next review 2026-04-23 focus: mechanics of signed assertions, and force the substrate-vs-authZ distinction on any nuszco-positioning question."
            }
          ]
        },
