            },
            {
              "date": "2026-04-15",
              "score": 0.67,
              "questions": 3,
              "correct": 2,
              "notes": "FAIL again. Q1: clean, all three categories with good examples (GitHub/AWS/VPN) - concrete examples gap from last session is closed. Q2: 3/4 handshake artifacts, missed ACS URL; signing cert role vague ('assert the IdP signage') - doesn't yet articulate signature verification / public-key crypto. Mark explicitly asked for a step-by-step walkthrough of the federation exchange, which was provided (setup 4 steps + runtime 6 steps). Q3: correctly said false but didn't name SCIM or JIT as the actual provisioning mechanisms - gap is connecting federation (trust setup) vs provisioning (user data channel) as separate concerns. Re-quiz tomorrow focusing on: ACS URL role, signature verification mechanics, SCIM-vs-JIT as the two ways users actually appear on SP."
            },
            {
              "date": "2026-04-22",
              "score": 0.7,
              "questions": 2,
              "correct": 1.4,
              "notes": "FAIL (3rd consecutive) but closest score yet. Used forced-retrieval stage before re-teach per failed-review protocol. Stage 1 retrieval: categories SOLID (SaaS/cloud/on-prem retained from 04-15 - that win is durable). Federation artifacts 3/4 AGAIN - MISSED ACS URL for the third consecutive session. This gap is now a persistent pattern across 3 reviews and is not absorbing from list-form teaching. Mark was blank on signature verification mechanics and on SCIM vs JIT - both taught fresh this session. Q1 (0.4): right asymmetric-crypto shape (federation-time cert + runtime hash + public-key decrypt) BUT confused the objects: described a 'new signing cert POSTS to ACS URL' (wrong - it's the signed assertion that POSTs, cert was exchanged at setup) and a 'gold standard cert vs new cert' comparison (wrong - comparison is hash-vs-decrypted-hash, not cert-vs-cert). Runtime object confusion: doesn't yet distinguish 'what rides in federation setup' from 'what rides at runtime.' Also skipped the failure-mode half of Q1. Q2 (1.0): 3/3 clean SCIM/JIT discrimination on first exposure - new engineer pre-provisioning (SCIM), contractor licenses (JIT), fast termination (SCIM). Marked answers with '?' uncertainty but reasoning was correct - knowledge present, confidence not yet. Q3 (oauth2 interleave) skipped - Mark self-managed fatigue, explicitly called out uncertainty. Respected. Q3 preserved as oauth2 probe for next session ('in nuszco’s Sign-in-with-Google PKCE flow, what role is Google playing - IdP/SP/both - and is the flow authN/authZ/both?'). Next review (2026-04-23) focus: (a) drill ACS URL directly not as part of a list, (b) object-level precision - what is a CERT, what is an ASSERTION, what is a SIGNATURE, what rides at setup vs runtime, (c) failure-mode reasoning (forged assertion = 'I am CEO' without sig check)."
            }
          ]
